Discover the various session functions of PHP. Explain its behavior.

SOLUTION:
In PHP, sessions allow you to store user data (variables) across multiple page requests. 
PHP provides a set of session functions to manage them. 

Common PHP Session Functions & Their Behavior:
1. session_start()
Starts a new session or resumes an existing one.
Must be called before any output is sent to the browser.
SYNTAX:
session_start();

2. $_SESSION (Superglobal Array)
Used to register/store variables in a session.
SYNTAX:
$_SESSION["user"] = "Rajesh"; 

3. session_id()
Returns the current session ID (a unique identifier for the session).
You can also pass a string to set a custom session ID.
SYNTAX:
echo session_id();

4. session_name()
Returns the name of the current session (default: PHPSESSID).
You can also set a custom session name before session_start().
SYNTAX:
echo session_name();

5. session_unset()
Frees all session variables but does not destroy the session itself.
SYNTAX:
session_unset();  // Clears all $_SESSION variables

6. session_destroy()
Destroys all data registered to a session.
Ends the session but does not unset the $_SESSION array until the script ends.
SYNTAX:
session_destroy();

7. session_regenerate_id()
Generates a new session ID, replacing the old one.
Commonly used for security (e.g., after login to prevent session fixation attacks).
SYNTAX:
session_regenerate_id(true);

8. session_get_cookie_params()
Returns an array with the current session cookie parameters (lifetime, path, domain, etc.).
SYNATX:
print_r(session_get_cookie_params());

9. session_set_cookie_params()
Sets the session cookie parameters (must be called before session_start()).
SYNTAX:
session_set_cookie_params(3600); // 1 hour

10. session_write_close()
Writes session data and ends the session.
Useful if you want to finish session handling but keep data accessible.
SYNTAX:
session_write_close();

SUMMARY:
Start/Resume Session: session_start()
Work with Variables: $_SESSION
Session ID/Name: session_id(), session_name()
Clear/Destroy: session_unset(), session_destroy()
Security: session_regenerate_id()
Cookies: session_get_cookie_params(), session_set_cookie_params()
Close Session Writing: session_write_close()
